\subsection*{Occupancy}

In order for occupancy methods to work the monitoring area has to be practical. Certain authors have advocated that  habitat units should be at the scale of territories, however this is contentious with other authors (such as Darryl MacKenzie) suggesting that is also appropriate to consider occupancy in terms of "use" rather than proxy territories. Regardless, you want your spatial units to larger enough to be repeatedly encounter the species should it be in the general vicinity. If units are too small then then the possibility of repeated detection became very low -- a situation not dissimilar to not recapturing individuals in mark-recapture.

If we use the polygon of the monitoring area as a guide and assume the an appropriate spatial unit is at 15 $\times$ 15 m (more-or-less equivalent to the current bait station spacing) then the area could accommodate 36 units. Each of these units could be further divided into 4 quadrants of 7.5 $\times$ 7.5 m, giving rise to 144 units (Figure \ref{fig:grid}).



