\subsection*{What might the true occupancy probability be?}

Based on an apparent detection rate of 4 individuals/208 trap nights across 47 Gee's minnow traps we can naively reinterpret the observed detection as being the product of the species being available for detection and the area in question being occupied (Figure \ref{fig:naive}). If we exclude the possibility that there is very high detection (as this should have resulted in some recaptures in previous surveys), and assume that the real detection rate although low, approximates that seen in the Alborn skink, and that individuals have exclusive territories then this may suggest that \mytilde 21\% of the area may be occupied.

